    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-21T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-21T06:00:00-05:00" n="159"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d159">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">856.001W64/53⅗: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-21T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 21, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 21—7:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1294. My 1273, May 20, 4 p.m. For the President.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Message of Her Majesty the Queen of the Netherlands to the President of the
                        United States.</p>
                    <p>I am very grateful for your personal message which the Ambassador of the
                        United States brought me this afternoon.</p>
                    <p>Your appreciation of the splendid resistance of my armed forces against
                        overwhelming numbers of enemy troops deeply touched me. In this appreciation
                        everyone will join who realizes the superhuman effort they made.</p>
                    <p>Your kind consideration of my personal welfare and that of my family is a
                        great comfort to me in these days of stress. If circumstances should call
                        for it—may God forbid its necessity—I will not fail to remember your
                        generous initiative. (Signed) Wilhelmina, May 20th, 1940.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
